Inflation in Europe jumped due to food
The accelerating inflation measured in the euro area is mainly due to constant growth in food prices.
The November price increase in 13 euro area countries was above expectations, with annual inflation registered 3.1 percent after 2.6 percent in October, reporting to the Luxembourg Union Statistical Office.
The official forecast only predicted 3 percent, reported by Bloomberg.
Unlike the US, British and Canadian Emissions Bank, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not reduced the basic interest rate, with a reduction in prices of raw materials rising and falling unemployment leading to an inflation spiral.
The ECB would like to keep inflation below 2%, but close to it.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in a preposterous situation: it must "predate" inflation so that it does not have to do anything about this later.
In Germany, November inflation represents 3.3 percent of the 15-year record; in Spain it then rose from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
Inflation in the euro area has skyrocketed due to sharply rising food and energy prices.
The term wheat prices rose by 88 percent, also the soy exchange rate reached the highest value since 1973.
Likewise, in 2007 it was necessary to pay significantly more for edible oil and dairy products.
The world’s oil price has risen by 52 percent this year, and last month, a barrel of black gold cost nearly $100.
According to the ECB, inflation will shift from 2.1 percent to 2.5 in 2008 this year, but will drop to 1.9 in 2009.
According to analysts, the 12-month inflation rate will remain at around 3 % over the next 3-4 months, but its average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to cut interest rates twice during 2008.
