In many places it is saved on disinfectants
This year more than a thousand cases of infection were registered in hospitals, mainly due to inappropriate use of antibiotics.
Hospital hygiene conditions, bed overfilling, overburdening staff do not help with disease control, says the Chief of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many places they also save on disinfectants.
Recently, MRSA infection was diagnosed in the trauma department of St. John's Hospital.
Antibacterial-resistant bacteria were discovered in a man who got into the hospital after a serious traffic accident.
Patient's been isolated.
A similar infection occurred at the same site early in the year.
The patient injured in a serious car accident was released home, but not long after he had to return with MRSA infection and because of the bacteria found in his body, one important surgery could not yet be performed.
By 10 December this year, 1,094 hospital infections caused by multi-resistance disease agents were reported to the Nesocomialis Surveillance National System, Karolina Böröczová, the Chief of the National Epidemiology Center, announced.
This means that so many infections caused by multi-resistance disease agents have been safely registered in hospitals, others are unknown.
Almost two thirds (683) of infections were caused by MRSA, or methiciline-oxacillin resistant to gold staphylococci.
Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria carry a third of the people in the nose without causing the disease.
Infections caused by SA (e.g. cervical inflammation, tonsil inflammation, skin infection, early infection) respond well to antibiotics and can be treated well.
However, if antibiotics are administered excessively or inappropriately, it develops from a bacteria that respond well to antibiotics that are highly resistant to antibiotics and that spread rapidly in inadequate hospital conditions.
In particular, in case of transient or permanent poor functioning of the immune system in patients with weakened organisms, low body weight or in patients over the years, it can cause serious hospital infections, such as early infection or blood poisoning - sepsis.
According to the chief physician of St John's Hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infection, similar infections are among the daily practice in hospitals.
"Infection must not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is not only there," Tibor Nyulasi said, "where the presence of the disease agent is not investigated."
Resisting Antibiotics
"We isolate these patients, care personnel treat them in rubber gloves, and we have the antibiotics needed to treat them," said Tibor Nyulasi.
Patients admitted to the hospital are first examined whether they are present in their MRSA organism, however, infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling is not in mode
The vast majority of hospital infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but the current conditions and conditions in home hospitals are not favourable to preventing the emergence and spread of multi-resistance disease agents, argues Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection occurs characteristically in hospitals and homes for the elderly, hospitals should immediately control the admitted patients and isolate MRSA carriers.
However, sampling of microbiological samples in Hungarian hospitals is not in the fashion.
The fact that the National Health Insurance Fund does not finance these examinations also plays a role.
Most cases are thus revealed, if the patient suffers from noticeable MRSA infection, said the chief of the epidemiological center.
The European Union has strict recommendations for appropriate treatment of antibiotics in the field of human medicine, and there are also home guidelines for the treatment of individual infections, diseases.
Antibiotic therapy should be targeted, or microbiological tests should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not do so in all cases.
The collection of microbiological samples is even more rare for basic and outpatient treatment, or outpatient treatment, was reported by Karolina Böröcz.
Saved on disinfectants
According to scientific evidence, MRSA spreads among patients most often through medical personnel.
Therefore, washing hands and using gloves and masks play a very important role, but there are also serious shortcomings in hospitals.
MRSA is transmitted by both drip infection and touch, but it is not always possible to isolate infected patients under the conditions of home hospitals.
On the contrary, the rooms are often crowded, the beds are often very close to each other, although from an epidemiological point of view patients should be at least 1.5 meters away from each other.
As Karolina Böröcz noted, unfortunately, we can also see that in hospitals that are in an unfavorable material situation they are saving on disinfectants, nurses are few and patients are many, thus increasing the chances of infection.
According to Karolina Böröcz, where the necessary protective measures are observed, similar infections are demonstrably less or further spread of the disease agent can be stopped.
Government program against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA infection is a huge expense for health insurance companies, which is why it is combated everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has written a MRSA prevention program, respectively, to reduce its occurrence.
The program seems to be successful, according to published data, MRSA infections in England show a declining trend.
The European Center for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) ranks among its priorities the prevention of the emergence of multi-resistent disease agents (including MRSAs), respectively hospital infections caused by these disease agents.
