Another EUR 400 million for infrastructure
On Friday in Budapest, Finance Minister János Veres and Marta Gajeck, Vice President of the European Investment Bank (EIB) signed an agreement on three loan frameworks worth EUR 400 million to support education, transport and environmental infrastructure as well as energy.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) approved a framework of EUR 300 million for the Hungarian budget financing of transport and environmental projects implemented under the aid of the Cohesion Fund, with the parties having previously concluded a loan agreement of EUR 100 million, the Treaty now signed concerns the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
Also, for the budget financing of projects related to education, the EUR 150 million loan agreement is used.
The EIB has approved EUR 300 million for this purpose in total, and the remaining EUR 150 million may be used later, with the extension of the credit agreement.
In the area of innovation, the parties signed a contract for €50 million, which the budget will mainly apply to the research-development project of the University of Debrecín.
There was also a talk at the meeting about the 4th metro route.
The Parties agree that, after Hungary has agreed with the EU on the details of the financing of the metro, it will revert to whether and how the original contract needs to be modified.
According to János Veres, this can happen in the first quarter of 2008.
The EIB has financed 113 projects in Hungary since 1990.
