Fodor and Hungarian 6 percent
According to information from the Minister for Environment and Water, Gábor Fodor will conclude meetings of experts on Tuesday, and the international conference on the climate regime will continue after 2012 after Wednesday's official launch with the meeting of ministers.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries of the world are discussing the Bali Travel Map, which addresses efforts following the period of reduction of emissions as defined by the Kyoto Protocol applicable until 2012.
At the moment, they are under heated debate between developing and developed countries.
The United States has also announced that they do not want to negotiate precise numbers now, although they tend to agree to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 percent by 2020, given the 1990 status.
Another major issue of the conference is whether developed countries will also accept, in addition to reducing emissions, the provision of both material and technological assistance to countries that rely on it.
The agreement was also born on subsidies for developing countries.
The subsidy fund, established by the Kyoto Protocol, will be led by the 16-member Governing Board, most likely under the World Environmental Protection Programme (GEF) at the UN - we can read in the Piac és Profit magazine.
Hungarian 6 percent
On behalf of Hungary, the Minister for Environment and Water, Gábor Fodor, supports the EU's efforts to maintain a leading role in efforts to global climate protection and to help create a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister stated that the EU is committed to reducing greenhouse gas emissions by 20 percent by 2020 compared to 1990 levels, independently of the success of adopting the post-2012 'agreement', and is prepared to commit to a 30% reduction if other developed regions of the world, respectively, are willing to accept responsibilities and commitments appropriate to their capabilities.
Gábor Fodor pointed out that the countries that joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 set the target of a 5.2 percent reduction, with the then 15 EU Member States committed to 8 percent.
Hungary's commitment is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 percent compared to 1985-87, which our country will meet. - It is recalled in the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
Bali is a big deal, because within two years there is a need to adopt an international agreement on long-term climate change policy, otherwise its entry into force would not be certain until 2012. In this case, the commitments to reduce the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by a new emission reduction system, the necessity of which the UN International Climate Change Scientific Council has also pointed out in its latest report - the IPCC, which is a Nobel Peace Prize winner.
This would lead to a delay in reducing emissions and an inevitable increase in the average temperature on Earth by more than 2 degrees Celsius, which, according to scientists, would have extremely serious and irreversible consequences.
