Political Capital: Hungarian Guard Raised Country Risk
The activities of the Hungarian Guard, founded with the support of the Jobbik Magyarszágért movement in August this year, according to the Division of Risk Analysis Division, the Political Capital Institute increased the political risk of Hungary and the whole area in several respects.
The "warning of risks" drawn up by the company states: in connection with the activities of the Hungarian Guard, the greatest political risk is that "the highlighting of already existing ethnic tensions between the Roma and non-Romani populations of Hungary may already take place in a short time with violent ethnic clashes".
The main reason is that the Hungarian Guard's political strategy is likely to be directed towards provoke such an action - it adds the research institute.
As he writes, all this can be explained by one of the greatest negligents of Hungarian political leaders: "public debate on the Roma issue has been left by representatives of public life to representatives of radical and extremist political groups who could build a political strategy on the Roma-Hungarian conflict."
This deepens the problem, makes normal dialogue impossible, strengthens extremists and increases the likelihood of violent conflicts - the Institute judges.
Moreover, according to the research institute, the Hungarian Guard's activities, due to the great attention of domestic and foreign media, have "broken largely the image of Hungary abroad, particularly as regards belief in the stability of the country and its democratic maturity".
The Institute recalls: part of the reorganization of Hungarian radical and ultra-right groups, which have been receiving ever greater publicity and vehemence since autumn 2006, is that several organizations have been formed in Hungary since summer 2007, which are called self-organizations "national militias".
"The common feature of these groupings is that they define themselves as civil associations, while openly proclaiming - even armed - the readiness of their members to perform defensive tasks (in the event of natural disasters, attack of their homeland, disturbance of order), plus pointing to the inability of the police, army, or state," he adds.
He further notes: all this is done in a way that tries to wrap up various political efforts built on the opposition of society to politics and parties into civilian robes.
Thus, emphasising civility and the form of a society in the case of these groupings is not only designed to avoid legal difficulties in judicial registration, but is also a political strategy.
According to the analysis, the Hungarian Guard’s activity is also a risk-enhancing factor in terms of neighbourly relations.
"In recent months, Hungary's Guards are pointing to several neighbouring states as a potential source of danger, ultra-nationalist political leaders of some neighbouring countries want to excuse their own anti-Hungarian policy by appealing to the formation of the Hungarian Guard.
All this can affect the political stability of the area," he adds.
According to the research institute, the formation of the Hungarian Guard in Central and Eastern Europe is not an isolated phenomenon, so political risks to the area as a whole have increased.
As he writes, the Hungarian Guard's activity resembles, for example, the Bulgarian National Guard, whose creation was announced in August 2007 by the ultra-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU).
Against the background of the formation of the Bulgarian Guard, there are mass Roma riots that broke out in one of the Sofia neighborhoods (Krasna Poljana).
She used the BNU to establish a guard, saying that the organization's goal was "national militia".
In the past 17 years, according to her, there has been "Gypsy terror" in Bulgaria, but the state has remained dormant and indifferent, reminiscent of the Institute of Political Capital.
