Compressed memory
After more than 60 years in a confidential regime, Nazi archives from Bad Arolsen, recounting the fates of 17.5 million victims of Hitler’s regime, open to the public.
47 million archival documents stored 27 km in Bad Arolsen (Hesse) have been accessible by this time only for "humanitarian" purposes, i.e. individually and specifically, at the request of the former victim or its authorized persons.
Eleven states responsible for managing archives - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May to open them to scientists and historians.
Since the ratification process for this agreement by all states is over, the opening took effect yesterday.
Sensitive information
The free access of historians to Bad Arolsen will allow to explore "especially the movements of prisoners, the population of camps and the health of forced workers", explains Reto Meistern, director of these archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (Cimité international de la Croix-rouge, CICR).
Until recently, several states, among them Germany, were opposed to accessing these nominal documents to the public, due to the sensitive nature of some information.
What are the supposed homosexuality or mental disability of some victims of deportation?
The registers of concentration camps or warrants drawn up by the Gestapo were collected after the war for the practical purpose of finding deported or forced labour subjected to civil citizens, bringing them proof of their internment in order to open the way for their compensation.
Today, more than 300 permanent employees in Bad Arolsen are still dealing with tens of thousands of individual applications.
However, for part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is only a limited benefit.
"Nothing fundamentally new can be expected from these documents", said Prof. Wolfgang Benz, director of the Center for the Study of Anti-Semitism of Berlin's Technische Universität in 2006.
