Congress approved MiFID transposition valid from 1 November
In parallel to parliamentary negotiations that were concluded today by the Congress vote on amendments incorporated by the Senate into the bill, the government subjected a public hearing to a regulation developing a new law, in order for both to enter into force before the end of the year.
The representatives of the parties have consistently highlighted the efforts of Members and Senators to negotiate and agree the best standard in order to guarantee investor protection and detailed regulation of the activities of the entities required for the effective functioning of the markets.
The MiFID Directive, which regulates the Securities Trading Act, foresees modernisation of financial markets while strengthening investor protection, improves the supervisory powers of the State Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and promotes cooperation between the various supervisory authorities of the European Union.
This new regulation will enable financial consultancy services to be provided to both specialised firms and natural or legal persons, and will create a new type of financial services (ESIS), financial consultancy companies (AFIs), which join securities companies, securities brokering offices and portfolio management companies.
In addition, the number of systems for the execution of operations with financial instruments is widened by adding multilateral trading systems and orders internalisation systems to regulated secondary markets, which will compete with current stockbrokers.
Furthermore, the Act obliges investment services companies to disseminate information on key aspects of their business profile, exposure to risk and methods of dealing with risk, and requires a statement of all transactions carried out to simplify supervision by CNMV.
During the negotiations on the Congress Trade Commission, several adjustments were included, among which the securitised claims were considered to be a "complicated" financial instrument due to the high risk to the investor, which was demonstrated by what occurred in the US with high risk mortgage debts (subprime).
Moreover, the transposition of the directive was used to legally establish the functions that bachelors in the field of economics and corporate governance can hold for 30 years after a royal decree was passed in 1977, setting out professional functions reserved for economists.
At the same time, the Senate has ranked the creation of new professions in the financial sector, such as an intermediary who will work externally, will not require permission from CNMV and will be able to provide product trading and customer acquisition services for various investment firms at the same time.
