There is a dispute between Russia and Ukraine over the prices of natural gas, and so the risk that Russian supplies of this fuel to Western Europe may be affected is increasing.
Most of the Russian fuel exported to the European Union (EU) is conducted through pipelines across Ukraine and any dispute between these two countries is closely monitored.
Kiev warned that if Moscow raised the prices of gas to Ukraine, Russia would charge higher transit fees.
The previous dispute between these two last year reduced supplies to EU states.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow comes when the Ukrainian government and the Russian state-owned gas monopoly, Gazprom, try to agree on how much Ukraine will have to pay for Russian gas in 2008.
Gazprom says he will have to charge Ukraine more because he agreed to pay up to 50% more for the gas he receives from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say that this could mean that Ukraine will have to pay 40% more for its deliveries from Gazprom.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states during negotiations," said Reuters Ukrainian Minister of Economy Anatoli Kinach to the Agency.
"Changes in gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the level of transit fees (to Western Europe) via Ukraine."
The last larger dispute between Moscow and Kiev caused a drop in supplies from Gazprom to Ukraine in January 2006.
This caused an overwhelming fall in exports to Western Europe, which sharply increased prices.
Russian gas represents one quarter of the supply to the European Union.
Russia has the largest gas reserves in the world, but much of them remain under-used.
