The climate of Venus may be a glimpse of the future of the Earth
Scientists announced yesterday that Venus could have once been a pleasant place to live.
Data from the orbiting European station show that the planet is even more similar to the headstrong twin of the Earth than previously thought.
Venus is Earth's closest planetary neighbor.
These two worlds are roughly the same size and orbit similar paths, but Venus is a little closer to the Sun.
Scientists now believe that billions of years ago Venus had conditions similar to those on Earth and could have been habitable.
But the recovered greenhouse effect caused by carbon dioxide, atmospheric erosion by solar radiation and lower rate of rotation sent Venus on a completely different path of development.
Today the planet is without water, the temperature on the surface is hot enough to melt lead and be ravaged by storms and hurricane winds.
Findings from the probe of the European Space Agency Venus Express, which studied the planet for one year, offer a moderate view of how the Earth could develop in the event of catastrophic climate change.
Professor Fred Taylor of the University of Oxford Physics Department and one of Venus Express' mission leaders said, "It is becoming more and more clear why the climate in Venus is so different than on Earth, although the planets themselves are otherwise quite alike.
"Our new data allows us to compile a scenario in which Venus began as well as Earth, perhaps even with a habitable environment, billions of years ago."
