Does the US credit card market affect the sub-prime crisis?
When blood is in the water, naturally, dorsal fins begin to wave around excitedly.
Now that the U.S. property market is wasting away, predators are targeting the credit card market there.
Goldman Sachs analysts say that credit card losses could reach $99 billion if sub-prime mortgages infected other consumer loan variants.
The signs of tension are obvious.
The number of defaults (in more than 30 days of payment delay) and debited accounts (accounts considered by the provider to be unenforceable) is increasing.
HSBC announced last month that it lost $1.4 billion on the US consumer credit market - also due to insolvent credit card loans.
But it is still too early for panic.
There are still few written-off accounts and inability to pay back.
According to the Moody's evaluation agency, the 3.89% insolvency rate in the third quarter was almost a full percentage point below average.
The worsening rates can be partly explained by technical reasons.
The change in the U.S. Personal Bankruptcy Act 2005 resulted in a sharp decline in the number of reported bankruptcies that make much of the credit card losses; the number of reports (and thus the number of write-offs) would therefore rise, regardless of whether the general conditions for borrowers worsened.
The sector also shows a good maturity rate, which shows how much consumers pay off their debts per month.
And trust in credit card security is solid, despite paralysis in other parts of structured finance.
Mr Dennis Moroney of TowerGroup's research firm predicts that their emissions for 2007 will be 25% larger than last year.
Direct routes for spreading infection between the subprime mortgage crisis and the credit card market certainly exist: when real estate property loans are drying out, consumers tend to owe themselves over credit cards.
Credit card publishers, however, view the cash flow rather than the value of the voucher items, so falling home prices may not necessarily mean a change in the credibility of borrowers.
They may even be advantageous for loan providers.
Consumer motivation to repay mortgages decreases when the value of their assets falls below the value of the loan; consequently, credit on cards shifts up to the list of priorities for repayment.
Card publishers can also respond faster and more flexibly to turbulent conditions than mortgage providers by changing interest rates or debt limits.
This should theoretically reduce the risks of a rapid price change of the guarantors.
"It doesn't happen that one beautiful morning we'll just reevaluate all the loans," says Gary Perlin, financial manager of Capital One.
Although the risk of an explosion in the form of sub-prime mortgages is low, the risk of gradual weakening is far more real.
